    one question per row: "do you match?". The query layer never hard-codes a
    filter; it asks a predicate. A new operator is a new class, zero engine code.
  * `Index` / `HashIndex` — the data structure that turns an equality lookup
    from an O(n) scan into an O(1) hit. A predicate can ALSO advertise the
    equality conditions it carries (`eq_conditions`), which is exactly what the
    query planner reads to decide "index or scan?".

Neither family imports the domain model, so it has no cycle with `models.py`.

🎙️ "The smart move is that a predicate does double duty: it can FILTER a row,
and it can DESCRIBE itself to the planner. So 'use the index' isn't a special
case bolted onto the engine — it falls out of asking the predicate what equality
conditions it holds."
"""

from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
from dataclasses import dataclass
from typing import Any


# ── INDEX: the equality-lookup accelerator ───────────────────────────────────
class Index(ABC):
    # ── WHY THIS CLASS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    # The abstraction the Table depends on so a column can be looked up without
    # scanning every row. Today the only impl is a hash index (equality, O(1));
    # tomorrow a sorted/tree index could add range lookups behind the same three
    # methods. Keeping it an interface is what makes that swap a new class.
    @abstractmethod
    def add(self, value: Any, rid: int) -> None:
        """Record that row `rid` now has this `value` in the indexed column."""
        raise NotImplementedError

    @abstractmethod
    def remove(self, value: Any, rid: int) -> None:
        """Forget that row `rid` had this `value` (on delete or before an update)."""
        raise NotImplementedError

    @abstractmethod
    def lookup(self, value: Any) -> set[int]:
        """Return the set of row ids whose indexed column equals `value`."""
        raise NotImplementedError


class HashIndex(Index):
    # ── WHY THIS CLASS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    # value -> set of row ids. Equality lookup becomes a single dict hit (O(1))
    # instead of walking the whole table. A SET (not a list) because the same
    # value can appear in many rows AND so remove() is O(1) and never leaves a
    # duplicate behind.
    def __init__(self, column: str) -> None:
        self.column = column
        self._buckets: dict[Any, set[int]] = {}

    def add(self, value: Any, rid: int) -> None:
        self._buckets.setdefault(value, set()).add(rid)

    def remove(self, value: Any, rid: int) -> None:
        bucket = self._buckets.get(value)
        if bucket is None:
            return                       # nothing indexed under this value — no-op
        bucket.discard(rid)

        if not bucket:
            del self._buckets[value]     # WHY: drop empty buckets so the map can't leak keys

    def lookup(self, value: Any) -> set[int]:
        # WHY: hand back a COPY so a caller iterating the result can't be hit by a
        #      concurrent mutation of the live bucket (and can't corrupt our state).
        return set(self._buckets.get(value, ()))

    def distinct_values(self) -> int:
        return len(self._buckets)


# ── PREDICATE: the row-filter Strategy ───────────────────────────────────────
class Predicate(ABC):
    # ── WHY THIS CLASS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    # The query layer's only knowledge of "what counts as a match". It answers
    # matches() per row, names the columns() it touches (so the engine can reject
    # an unknown column before scanning), and advertises eq_conditions() so the
    # planner can pick an index without knowing the concrete predicate type.
    @abstractmethod
    def matches(self, values: dict[str, Any]) -> bool:
        """True if a row's column->value map satisfies this predicate."""
        raise NotImplementedError

    @abstractmethod
    def columns(self) -> set[str]:
        """Every column this predicate reads — used to validate against the schema."""
        raise NotImplementedError

    def eq_conditions(self) -> list[tuple[str, Any]]:
        """(column, value) equality pairs the planner may resolve via an index.

        Default: none. Only `Eq` (and `And`, by collecting its children) carries
        equality conditions a hash index can accelerate.
        """
        return []


